    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1985-03-08T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1985-03-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="379"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d379">
                <head>379. Memorandum From the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                        (<persName corresp="#p_MRC_1">McFarlane</persName>) to President <persName
                        corresp="#p_RR_1">Reagan</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d379fn1">Source: Reagan Library, <persName
                            corresp="#p_KS_1">Sven Kraemer</persName> Files, Chrons, March 1985
                        Chron File: [No.44–No.46]. Secret. Sent for action. Prepared by <persName
                            corresp="#p_KS_1">Kraemer</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_LRE_1"
                            >Linhard</persName>. <persName corresp="#p_RR_1">Reagan</persName>
                        initialed the memorandum, indicating he saw it.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1985-03-08">March 8, 1985</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Principals’ Views on Geneva Options</item>
                </list>
                <p>Secretaries <persName corresp="#p_SGP_1">George Shultz</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_WCW_1">Cap Weinberger</persName> and <gloss target="#t_ACDA_1"
                        >ACDA</gloss> Director <persName corresp="#p_AKL_1">Kenneth
                        Adelman</persName> have sent separate memoranda to you forwarding their
                    views on preferred options for the Geneva negotiators.</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Secretary <persName corresp="#p_SGP_1"
                        >Shultz</persName>’s</hi> memorandum (Tab A)<note n="2" xml:id="d379fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_SGP_1">Shultz</persName>’s memorandum is not attached,
                        but an unsigned copy, dated March 6, is in the Reagan Library, <persName
                            corresp="#p_KS_1">Sven Kraemer</persName> Files, Chrons, March 1985
                        Chron File: [No.21–No.25].</note> endorses <gloss target="#t_START_1"
                        >START</gloss> Option 3, arguing that while this option permits more
                    ballistic missile warheads than our current <gloss target="#t_START_1"
                        >START</gloss> proposal (i.e., far more than 5,000), it seeks <pb
                        facs="1448" n="1407" xml:id="pg_1407"/> to cut the most destabilizing
                    categories (i.e., warheads on <gloss target="#t_MIRV_1">MIRVed</gloss> missiles
                    and heavy <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">ICBMs</gloss>) and would set important
                    numericals limit on air-launched cruise missiles (<gloss target="#t_ALCM_1"
                        >ALCMs</gloss>) by aggregating these with ballistic missile warheads. For
                        <gloss target="#t_INF_1">INF</gloss>, <persName corresp="#p_SGP_1"
                        >Shultz</persName> argues in favor of a new initiative incorporated in
                    Option 2 that, in his view, properly amplifies previous positions while
                    sustaining <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> and Allied public opinion. On
                    Defense and Space, he states that to avoid focus on <gloss target="#t_SDI_1"
                        >SDI</gloss> as an obstacle, the <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> must
                    avoid being perceived as standing pat on <gloss target="#t_START_1"
                        >START</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_INF_1">INF</gloss>.</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Secretary <persName corresp="#p_WCW_1"
                        >Weinberger</persName>’s</hi> memorandum (Tab B)<note n="3" xml:id="d379fn3">
                        <persName corresp="#p_WCW_1">Weinberger</persName>’s memorandum is not
                        attached, but an undated, unsigned copy is in the Reagan Library, <persName
                            corresp="#p_KS_1">Sven Kraemer</persName> Files, Chrons, March 1985
                        Chron File: [No.21–No.25].</note> cautions against moving too rapidly on
                        <gloss target="#t_START_1">START</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_INF_1"
                        >INF</gloss> as time is needed to build support for <gloss target="#t_SDI_1"
                        >SDI</gloss> and as rapid progress in <gloss target="#t_START_1"
                        >START</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_INF_1">INF</gloss> would build pressure
                    for <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> concessions on <gloss target="#t_SDI_1"
                        >SDI</gloss>. Concerning <gloss target="#t_START_1">START</gloss>, <persName
                        corresp="#p_WCW_1">Weinberger</persName> endorses Option 5 as simplifying
                    constraints to two measures (warheads and throwweight) as opening with a
                    proposal for truly deep reductions to 4,000 warheads after 12 years, and as thus
                    taking the Soviets at their word on favoring “radical reductions,” while
                    offering substantial flexibility on various tradeoffs during the course of the
                    negotiations. For <gloss target="#t_INF_1">INF</gloss>, <persName
                        corresp="#p_WCW_1">Weinberger</persName> endorses Option 1, and strongly
                    criticizes Option 2’s “equal percentage reduction” concept as moving us far from
                    our current concept of zero-zero and of global equality and as leaving more
                    Soviet than <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> missiles in place.</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">
                        <gloss target="#t_ACDA_1">ACDA</gloss> Director <persName corresp="#p_AKL_1"
                            >Adelman</persName>’s</hi> memorandum (Tab C)<note n="4"
                        xml:id="d379fn4">
                        <persName corresp="#p_AKL_1">Adelman</persName>’s memorandum is not
                        attached, but a copy, dated March 6, is ibid.</note> is silent on <gloss
                        target="#t_INF_1">INF</gloss> and Defense/Space issues, but endorses <gloss
                        target="#t_START_1">START</gloss> Option 6 as an elaboration of our current
                    position (Option 1) and as providing a long-term “road map” outlining a path to
                    our long-term goal, without tying our negotiators to a specific tactic.</p>
                <p>In addition, Senator <persName corresp="#p_TJG_1">Tower</persName> has sent a
                    memorandum (Tab D)<note n="5" xml:id="d379fn5">
                        <persName corresp="#p_TJG_1">Tower</persName>’s memorandum is not attached,
                        but a copy, dated March 6, is ibid.</note> to <gloss target="#t_NSC_1"
                        >NSC</gloss> Staff outlining his views as to how Option 1 (our current
                    position), which he favors, can be enhanced to make it more dynamic. We are
                    drawing on several of his suggestions.</p>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">Recommendation</p>
                <p>That you review the attachments together with the proposed National Security
                    Decision Memorandum draft which is being provided in a separate package.<note
                        n="6" xml:id="d379fn6">
                        <persName corresp="#p_RR_1">Reagan</persName> did not indicate his approval
                        or disapproval of the recommendation.</note>
                </p>
            </div>
